# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iec-62700
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A **19-inch rack** is a standardized frame or enclosure for mounting multiple electronic equipment modules.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Each module has a front panel that is 19 inches (482.6 mm) wide.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The 19 inch dimension includes the edges or *ears* that protrude from each side of the equipment, allowing the module to be fastened to the rack frame with screws or bolts.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Common uses include computer servers, telecommunications equipment and networking hardware, audiovisual production gear, professional audio equipment, and scientific equipment.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Equipment designed to be placed in a rack is typically described as **rack-mount**/**rack-mountable**, a **rack-mount instrument**, **rack-mounted system**, or **rack-mount chassis**.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The rack may include subracks or shelves.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The height of the mountable equipment is standardized as multiples of 1.75 inches (44.45 mm) or one *rack unit* or *U* (less commonly *RU*).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The industry-standard rack cabinet is 42U tall; however, many data centers have racks taller than this.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The term **relay rack** appeared first in the late 19th century, in the world of telephony.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] By 1911, the term was also being used in railroad signaling.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] There is little evidence that the dimensions of these early racks were standardized.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch rack format with rack units of 1.75 inches (44.45 mm) was established as a standard by AT&T around 1922 in order to reduce the space required for repeater and termination equipment in a telephone company central office.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The earliest repeaters from 1914 were installed in ad hoc fashion on shelves, in wooden boxes and cabinets.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Once serial production started, they were built into custom-made racks, one per repeater.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] But in light of the rapid growth of the toll network, the engineering department of AT&T undertook a systematic redesign, resulting in a family of modular factory-assembled panels all "designed to mount on vertical supports spaced 191⁄2 inches between centers.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] By 1934, it was an established standard with holes tapped for 12-24 screws with alternating spacings of 1.25 inches (31.75 mm) and 0.5 inches (12.70 mm).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch rack format has remained constant while the technology that is mounted within it has changed considerably and the set of fields to which racks are applied has greatly expanded.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch (482.6 mm) standard rack arrangement is widely used throughout the telecommunications, computing, audio, video, entertainment and other industries, though the Western Electric 23-inch standard, with holes on 1-inch (25.4 mm) centers, is still used in legacy ILEC/CLEC facilities.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Nineteen-inch racks in two-post or four-post form hold most equipment in enterprise data centers, Internet service provider facilities, and professionally designed corporate server rooms, although hyperscale computing typically use wider racks.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] They allow for dense hardware configurations without occupying excessive floor space or requiring shelving.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Nineteen-inch racks are also often used to house professional audio and video equipment, including amplifiers, effects units, interfaces, headphone amplifiers, and even small-scale audio mixers.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A third common use for rack-mounted equipment is industrial power, control, and automation hardware.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Typically, a piece of equipment being installed has a front panel height 1⁄32 inch (0.031 in; 0.79 mm) less than the allotted number of Us.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Thus, a 1U rackmount computer is not 1.750 inches (44.5 mm) tall but is 1.719 inches (43.7 mm) tall.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] If *n* is the number of rack units, the ideal formula for panel height is *h* = 1.75*n* − 0.031 for calculating in inches, and *h* = 44.45*n* − 0.794 for calculating in millimeters.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] This gap allows a bit of room above and below an installed piece of equipment so it may be removed without binding on the adjacent equipment.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Originally, the mounting holes were tapped with a particular screw thread.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] When rack rails are too thin to tap, rivet nuts or other threaded inserts can be used, and when the particular class of equipment to be mounted is known in advance, some of the holes can be omitted from the mounting rails.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Threaded mounting holes in racks where the equipment is frequently changed are problematic because the threads can be damaged or the mounting screws can break off; both problems render the mounting hole unusable.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Tapping large numbers of holes that may never be used is expensive; nonetheless, tapped-hole racks are still in use, generally for hardware that rarely changes.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Examples include telephone exchanges, network cabling panels, broadcast studios and some government and military applications.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The tapped-hole rack was first replaced by clearance-hole (Round Hole, Round Unthreaded Holes, and Versa Rail) racks.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The holes are large enough to permit a bolt to be freely inserted through without binding, and bolts are fastened in place using cage nuts.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] In the event of a nut being stripped out or a bolt breaking, the nut can be easily removed and replaced with a new one.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Production of clearance-hole racks is less expensive.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The next innovation in rack design has been the square-hole rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Square-hole racks allow boltless mounting, such that the rack-mount equipment only needs to insert through and hook down into the lip of the square hole.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Installation and removal of hardware in a square-hole rack is very easy and boltless, where the weight of the equipment and small retention clips are all that is necessary to hold the equipment in place.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Older equipment meant for round-hole or tapped-hole racks can still be used, with the use of cage nuts made for square-hole racks.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable equipment is traditionally mounted by bolting or clipping its front panel to the rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Within the IT industry, it is common for network/communications equipment to have multiple mounting positions, including tabletop and wall mounting, so rack-mountable equipment will often feature L-brackets that must be screwed or bolted to the equipment prior to mounting in a 19-inch rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] With the prevalence of 23-inch racks in the Telecoms industry, the same practice is also common, but with equipment having 19-inch and 23-inch brackets available, enabling them to be mounted in existing racks.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A key structural weakness of front-mounted support is the bending stress placed on the mounting brackets of the equipment and the rack itself.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] As a result, 4-post racks have become common, featuring a mirrored pair of rear mounting posts.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Servers and deep pieces of equipment are often mounted using rails that are bolted to the front and rear posts (as above, it is common for such rails to have an adjustable depth), allowing the equipment to be supported by four posts, while also enabling it to be easily installed and removed.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] This, of course, varies by manufacturer, the design of the rack and its purpose, but through common constraining factors (such as raised-floor tile dimensions), these dimensions have become quite common.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The extra width and depth enable cabling to be routed with ease (also helping to maintain the minimum bend radius for fiber and copper cables) and deeper equipment to be utilized.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A common feature in IT racks is mounting positions for *zero-U* accessories, such as power distribution units (PDUs) and vertical cable managers and ducts, that utilize the space between the rear rails and the side of the rack enclosure.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The strength required of the mounting posts means they are invariably not merely flat strips but actually a wider folded strip arranged around the corner of the rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The posts are usually made of steel of around 2 mm thickness (the official standard recommends a minimum of 1.9 mm), or of slightly thicker aluminum.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Racks, especially two-post racks, are often secured to the floor or adjacent building structure so as not to fall over.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] This is usually required by local building codes in seismic zones.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] According to Telcordia Technologies Generic Requirements document GR-63-CORE, during an earthquake, telecommunications equipment is subjected to motions that can over-stress the equipment framework, circuit boards, and connectors.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The amount of motion and resulting stress depends on the structural characteristics of the building and framework in which the equipment is contained and the severity of the earthquake.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Seismic racks rated according to GR-63, *NEBS Requirements: Physical Protection,* are available, with Zone 4 representing the most demanding environment.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] GR-3108, *Generic Requirements for Network Equipment in the Outside Plant (OSP),* specifies the usable opening of seismic-compliant 19-inch racks.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Heavy equipment or equipment that is commonly accessed for servicing, for which attaching or detaching at all four corners simultaneously would pose a problem, is often not mounted directly onto the rack but instead is mounted via rails (or slides).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A pair of rails is mounted directly onto the rack, and the equipment then slides into the rack along the rails, which support it.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] When in place, the equipment may also then be bolted to the rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The rails may also be able to fully support the equipment in a position where it has been slid clear of the rack; this is useful for inspection or maintenance of equipment, which will then be slid back into the rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Some rack slides even include a tilt mechanism allowing easy access to the top or bottom of rack-mounted equipment when it is fully extended from the rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A rails kit may include a cable management arm (CMA), which folds the cables attached to the server and allows them to expand neatly when the server is slid out, without being disconnected.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] When there is a large number of computers in a single rack, it is impractical for each one to have its own separate keyboard, mouse, and monitor.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Instead, a KVM switch or LOM software is used to share a single keyboard/video/mouse set amongst many different computers.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Since the mounting hole arrangement is vertically symmetric, it is possible to mount rack-mountable equipment upside-down.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] However, not all equipment is suitable for this type of mounting.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] For instance, most optical disc players will not work upside-down because the driving motor mechanism does not grip the disc.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A standard 19-inch server rack cabinet is typically 42u in height, 600 millimetres (24 in) wide, and 36 inches (914.40 mm) deep.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] This comprises a volume of 974 L, or just under a cubic meter.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Newer server rack cabinets come with adjustable mounting rails, allowing the user to place the rails at a shorter depth if needed.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] There are a multitude of specialty server racks, including soundproof server racks, air-conditioned server racks, NEMA-rated, seismic-rated, open frame, narrow, and even miniature 19-inch racks for smaller applications.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Cabinets are generally sized to be no wider than the standard 24-inch-wide (610 mm) floor tiles used in most data centers.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Racks carrying telecom equipment like routers and switches often have extra width to accommodate the many cables on the sides.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] 19-inch equipment that needs to be moved often or protected from harsh treatment can be housed in a *road case* approved by the Air Transport Association of America (ATA), sometimes also referred to as a *flight case*.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Road cases typically have plywood sides laminated with polyvinyl chloride (PVC), extruded aluminum edges, steel corners, handles, and latches.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Larger cases typically have wheels for easy transport.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Road case racks come in different heights based on the 1U standard and different depths.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Non-isolated cases simply mount 19-inch mounting posts inside the case.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] To protect equipment from shock and vibration, road rack cases use an inner and outer case.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] These cases can be isolated by thick layers of foam or may use spring-loaded shock mounting.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Touring musicians, theatrical productions and sound and light companies use road case racks.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Rack strips used for road cases come in 2 types: single angle and double angle.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Double-angle rack strips offer better structural strength and an additional mounting face for cable management or additional support for heavy equipment.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] In 1965, a durable fiber-reinforced plastic 19-inch rackmount case was patented by ECS Composites and became widely used in military and commercial applications for electronic deployment and operation.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Rackmount cases are also constructed of thermo-stamped composite, carbon fiber, and DuPont's Kevlar for military and commercial uses.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Portable rack cases using a rotary-molded polyethylene outer shell are a lower-cost alternative to the more durable ATA-approved case.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] These cases are marketed to musicians and entertainers for equipment not subject to frequent transportation and rough handling.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The polyethylene shell is not fiberglass reinforced and is not rigid.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The shape of small cases is maintained by the rack rails and the cover seal extrusions alone.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Larger cases are further reinforced with additional plywood or sheet metal.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The outer shell is frequently embossed in a self-mating pattern to combat the tendency for stacked cases to deform slightly, creating a slope that encourages the upper case to slide off.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The cases typically use extruded aluminum bands at the ends of the body with tongue-and-groove mating to like bands for the covers.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] End covers are typically secured with either a simple draw latch or a rotary cam *butterfly* latch, named for the shape of the twist handle.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] There is no standard for airflow and cooling of rack-mounted equipment.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A variety of airflow patterns can be found, including front intakes and rear exhausts, as well as side intakes and exhausts.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Low-wattage devices may not employ active cooling, but use only passive thermal radiation and convection to dissipate heat.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] For rack-mounted computer servers, devices generally intake air on the front and exhaust on the rear.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] This prevents circular airflows where hot exhaust air is recirculated through an adjacent device and causes overheating.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Although open-frame racks are the least expensive, they also expose air-cooled equipment to dust, lint, and other environmental contamination.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] An enclosed sealed cabinet with forced air fans permits air filtration to protect equipment from dust.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Large server rooms will often group rack cabinets together so that racks on both sides of an aisle are either front-facing or rear-facing, which simplifies cooling by supplying cool air to the front of the racks and collecting hot air from the rear of the racks.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] These aisles may themselves be enclosed in a cold air containment tunnel so that cooling air does not travel to other parts of the building where it is not needed or mixes with hot air, making it less efficient.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Raised or false floor cooling in server rooms can serve a similar purpose; they permit cooling airflow to equipment through the underfloor space to the underside of enclosed rack cabinets.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A difficulty with forced air fan cooling in rack equipment is that fans can fail due to age or dust.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The fans themselves can be difficult to replace.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] In the case of network equipment, it may be necessary to unplug 50 or more cables from the device, remove the device from the rack, and then disassemble the device chassis to replace the fans.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] However, some rack equipment has been designed to make fan replacement easy, using quick-change fan trays that can be accessed without removing the cabling or the device from the rack, and in some cases without turning off the device so that operation is uninterrupted during replacement.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A rack's mounting fixture consists of two parallel metal strips (also referred to as *posts* or *panel mounts*) standing vertically.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The posts are each 0.625 inches (15.88 mm) wide, and are separated by a gap of 17.75 inches (450.85 mm), giving an overall rack width of 19 inches (482.60 mm).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The posts have holes in them at regular intervals, with both posts matching, so that each hole is part of a horizontal pair with a center-to-center distance of 18.28–18.34 inches (464.2–465.8 mm).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The holes in the posts are arranged vertically in repeating sets of three, with center-to-center separations of 0.5, 0.625, 0.625 inches (12.70, 15.88, 15.88 mm).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The hole pattern thus repeats every 1.75 inches (44.45 mm).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Holes so arranged can either be tapped (usually 10-32 UNF thread, or, less often, 6mm metric) or have square holes for cage nuts.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Racks are vertically divided into regions, 44.45 millimetres (1.75 in) in height.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Each region has three complete hole pairs on each side.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The holes are centered at 6.35 millimetres (0.25 in), 22.25 millimetres (0.88 in), and 38.1 millimetres (1.50 in) from the top or bottom of the region.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Such a region is commonly known as a **U**, for *unit*, **RU** for *rack unit* or, in German, **HE**, for *Höheneinheit*.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Heights within racks are measured by this unit.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable equipment is usually designed to occupy some integer number of U.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] For example, an oscilloscope might be 4U high.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable computers and servers are mostly between 1U and 4U high.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A blade server enclosure might require 10U.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Occasionally, one may see fractional U devices, such as a 1.5U server or devices that are just 22.5 or 15 cm in width, allowing for 2 or 3 such devices to be installed side by side, but these are much less common.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The height of a rack can vary from a few inches, such as in a broadcast console, to a floor-mounted rack whose interior is 45 rack units (200.2 centimetres or 78.82 inches) high.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Many wall-mounted enclosures for industrial equipment use 19-inch racks.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Some telecommunications and networking equipment is available in a narrower 10-inch format with the same unit height as a standard 19-inch rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] This standard is also gaining in popularity with hobbyists with limited space at their disposal.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Frames for holding rotary-dial telephone equipment, such as step-by-step telephone switches, were generally 11 feet 6 inches (3.51 m) high.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A series of studies led to the adoption of frames 7 feet (2.1 m) high, with modular widths in multiples of 1 foot 1 inch (0.33 m)—most often 2 feet 2 inches (0.66 m) wide.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The **ETSI rack** is defined by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETS 300 119).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The distance of the right edge of the right mounting rail to the left edge of the left mounting rail is 535 millimetres (21.1 in).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] As 535 mm is very close to 21 inches, these racks are sometimes called *21-inch racks*.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The gap between the posts is 500 millimetres (19.69 in).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] As 19-inch equipment has a maximum width of 17+1⁄4 inches (438.15 mm), they can easily be mounted in an ETSI rack by means of an ETSI bracket or adapter plate.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] In contrast to the 19-inch standards, ETSI also defined the size of the rack enclosure: the four allowed widths are 150, 300, 600, 900 millimetres (5.9, 11.8, 23.6, 35.4 in) and two allowed depths are 300 and 600 millimetres (12 and 24 in).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Hole spacing is 25 millimetres (0.98 in).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] A 23-inch (580 mm) rack is used for housing telephone (primarily), computer, audio and other equipment – although it is less common than the 19-inch rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The size denotes the width of the faceplate for the installed equipment.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The rack unit is a measure of vertical spacing and is common to both the 19 and 23-inch racks.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Hole spacing is either on 1-inch (25 mm) centers (Western Electric standard), or the same as for 19-inch (482.6 mm) racks (0.625 in or 15.9 mm spacing).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Open Rack is a mounting system designed by the Open Compute Project that has the same outside dimensions as typical 19-inch racks (e.g., 600 mm width), but internally supports wider equipment modules of 547 millimetres (21.5 in).
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] OpenVPX is an industry standard for modules that can be installed in a chassis in defense applications.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The modules can provide a variety of functions, similar to equipment in a rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Eurorack is a standard generally used in electronic music production to install components of a modular synthesizer, an electronic music instrument.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] This is achieved with a rack mounting system specific to the standard.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Eurocard is an IEEE standard format for printed circuit board (PCB) cards that can be plugged together into a standard chassis, which, in turn, can be mounted in a 19-inch rack.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] The chassis consists of a series of slotted card guides on the top and bottom, into which the cards are slid so they stand on end, like books on a shelf.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] At the spine of each card is one or more connectors which plug into mating connectors on a backplane that closes the rear of the chassis.
[src:iec-62700/19-inch-rack] Several standards such as VMEbus (Versa Module Eurocard bus), STEbus, PCI eXtensions for Instrumentation, openGear and others were developed, which share goals with Eurocard.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:iec-62700/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] AES3 was jointly developed by the Audio Engineering Society (AES) and the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) and so is also known as **AES/EBU**.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The standard was first published in 1985 and was revised in 1992 and 2003.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] AES3 has been incorporated into the International Electrotechnical Commission's standard **IEC 60958**, and is available in a consumer-grade variant known as S/PDIF.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The development of standards for digital audio interconnect for both professional and domestic audio equipment, began in the late 1970s in a joint effort between the Audio Engineering Society and the European Broadcasting Union, and culminated in the publishing of AES3 in 1985.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The AES3 standard has been revised in 1992 and 2003 and is published in AES and EBU versions.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Early on, the standard was frequently known as AES/EBU.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Variants using different physical connections are specified in IEC 60958.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] These are essentially consumer versions of AES3 for use within the domestic high fidelity environment using connectors more commonly found in the consumer market.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] These variants are commonly known as S/PDIF.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The AES3 standard parallels part 4 of the international standard IEC 60958.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Of the physical interconnection types defined by IEC 60958, two are in common use.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Type I connections use balanced, three-conductor, 110-ohm twisted pair cabling with XLR connectors.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Type I connections are most often used in professional installations and are considered the standard connector for AES3.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The hardware interface is usually implemented using RS-422 line drivers and receivers.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] IEC 60958 Type II defines an unbalanced electrical or optical interface for consumer electronics applications.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The precursor of the IEC 60958 Type II specification was the Sony/Philips Digital Interface, or S/PDIF.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Both were based on the original AES/EBU work.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] S/PDIF and AES3 are interchangeable at the protocol level, but at the physical level, they specify different electrical signalling levels and impedances, which may be significant in some applications.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] AES/EBU signals can also be run using unbalanced BNC connectors with a 75-ohm coaxial cable.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The unbalanced version has a very long transmission distance as opposed to the 150 meters maximum for the balanced version.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The AES-3id standard defines a 75-ohm BNC electrical variant of AES3.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] This uses the same cabling, patching and infrastructure as analogue or digital video, and is thus common in the broadcast industry.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The low-level protocol for data transmission in AES3 and S/PDIF is largely identical, and the following discussion applies for S/PDIF, except as noted.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] AES3 was designed primarily to support stereo PCM encoded audio in either DAT format at 48 kHz or CD format at 44.1 kHz.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] No attempt was made to use a carrier able to support both rates; instead, AES3 allows the data to be run at *any* rate, and encoding the clock and the data together using biphase mark code (BMC).
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Each audio sample (of up to 24 bits) is combined with four flag bits and a synchronisation preamble which is four time slots long to make a *subframe* of 32 time slots.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Two subframes (A and B, normally used for left and right audio channels) make a **frame**.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Frames contain 64 bit periods and are produced once per audio sample period.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] At the highest level, each 192 consecutive frames are grouped into an *audio block*.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] While samples repeat each frame time, metadata is only transmitted once per audio block.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] At 48 kHz sample rate, there are 250 audio blocks per second, and 3,072,000 time slots per second supported by a 6.144 MHz biphase clock.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The synchronisation preamble is a specially coded *preamble* that identifies the subframe and its position within the audio block.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Preambles are not normal BMC-encoded data bits, although they do still have zero DC bias.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The three preambles are called X, Y, Z in the AES3 standard; and M, W, B in IEC 958 (an AES extension).
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The 8-bit preambles are transmitted in the time allocated to the first four time slots of each subframe (time slots 0 to 3).
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Any of the three marks the beginning of a subframe.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] X or Z marks the beginning of a frame, and Z marks the beginning of an audio block.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] In two-channel AES3, the preambles form a pattern of ZYXYXYXY..., but it is straightforward to extend this structure to additional channels (more subframes per frame), each with a Y preamble, as is done in the MADI protocol.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] There is one channel status bit in each subframe, a total of 192 bits or 24 bytes for each channel in each block.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] Between the AES3 and S/PDIF standards, the contents of the 192-bit channel status word differ significantly, although they agree that the first channel status bit distinguishes between the two.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] In the case of AES3, the standard describes, in detail, the function of each bit.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] SMPTE timecode data can be embedded within AES3 signals.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] It can be used for synchronization and for logging and identifying audio content.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] It is embedded as a 32-bit binary word in bytes 18 to 21 of the channel status data.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The AES11 standard provides information on the synchronization of digital audio structures.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] the AES52 standard describes how to insert unique identifiers into an AES3 bit stream.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] SMPTE 2110-31 defines how to encapsulate an AES3 data stream in Real-time Transport Protocol packets for transmission over an IP network using the SMPTE 2110 IP based multicast framework.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] SMPTE 302M-2007 defines how to encapsulate an AES3 data stream in an MPEG transport stream for television applications.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] AES3 digital audio format can also be carried over an Asynchronous Transfer Mode network.
[src:iec-62700/aes3] The standard for packing AES3 frames into ATM cells is AES47.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The Audio Engineering Society (AES) published AES47 in 2002.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The method described by AES47 is also published by the International Electrotechnical Commission as **IEC 62365**.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] Many professional audio systems are now combined with telecommunication and IT technologies to provide new functionality, flexibility and connectivity over both local and wide area networks.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] AES47 was developed to provide a standardised method of transporting the standard digital audio per AES3 over telecommunications networks that provide a quality of service required by many professional low-latency live audio uses.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] AES47 may be used directly between specialist audio devices or in combination with telecommunication and computer equipment with suitable network interfaces.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] In both cases, AES47 the same physical structured cable used as standard by the telecommunications networks.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] Common network protocols like Ethernet use large packet sizes, which produce a larger minimum latency.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] Asynchronous transfer mode divides data into 48-byte *cells* which provide lower latency.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The original work was carried out at the British Broadcasting Corporation’s R&D department and published as "White Paper 074", which established that this approach provides the necessary performance for professional media production.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] AES47 was originally published in 2002 and was republished with minor revisions in February 2006.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] Amendment 1 to AES47 was published in February 2009, adding code points in the ATM Adaptation Layer Parameters Information Element to signal that the time to which each audio sample relates can be identified as specified in AES53.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The change in thinking from traditional ATM network design is not to necessarily use ATM to pass IP traffic (apart from management traffic) but to use AES47 in parallel with standard Ethernet structures to deal with extremely high performance secure media streams.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] AES47 has been developed to allow the simultaneous transport and switched distribution of a large number of AES3 linear audio streams at different sample frequencies.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] AES47 can support any of the standard AES3 sample rates and word size.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] AES11 Annex D (the November 2005 printing or version of AES11-2003) shows an example method to provide isochronous timing relationships for distributed AES3 structures over asynchronous networks such as AES47 where reference signals may be locked to common timing sources such as GPS.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] AES53 specifies how timing markers within AES47 can be used to associate an absolute time stamp with individual audio samples as described in AES47 Amendment 1.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] An additional standard has been published by the Audio Engineering Society to extend AES3 digital audio carried as AES47 streams to enable this to be transported over standard physical Ethernet hardware.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] This additional standard is known as AES51-2006.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] For minimum latency, AES47 uses "raw" ATM cells, ATM adaptation layer 0.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] Each ATM virtual circuit negotiates the parameters of a stream at connection time.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] In addition to the same rate and number of channels (which may be more than the 2 supported by AES3), the negotiation covers the number of bits per sample and the presence of an optional data byte.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The total must be 1, 2, 3, 4 or 6 bytes per sample, so it evenly divides the ATM cell size.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] AES3 uses 4 bytes per sample (24 bits of sample plus the optional data byte), but AES47 supports additional formats.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The optional data byte contains four "ancillary" bits corresponding to the AES3 VUCP bits.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] However, the P (parity) bit is replaced by a B bit which is set on the first sample of each audio block, and clear at all other times.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] This serves the same function as the B (or Z) synchronization preamble.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The other half of the data byte contains three "data protection" bits for error control and a sequencing bit.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The concatenation of the sequencing bits from all samples in a cell (combined little-endian) form a sequencing word of 8, 12, 16, or 24 bits.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The first four bits of the sequencing word are a sequencing number, used to detect dropped cells.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] This increments by 1 for each cell transmitted.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The second four bits are for error detection, with bit 7 being an even parity bit for the first byte.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] The third four bits, if present, are a second sequencing number which can be used to align multiple virtual circuits.
[src:iec-62700/aes47] This standard may be studied by downloading a copy of the latest version from the AES standards web site as AES53-2018.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] The first standard for C was published by ANSI.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] Although this document was subsequently adopted by ISO/IEC and subsequent revisions published by ISO/IEC have been adopted by ANSI, "ANSI C" is still used to refer to the standard.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] While some software developers use the term ISO C, others are standards-body neutral and use Standard C.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] Informal specification in 1978 (Brian Kernighan and Dennis Ritchie book *The C Programming Language*).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] In 1983, the American National Standards Institute formed a committee, X3J11, to establish a standard specification of C.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] In 1985, the first Standard Draft was released, sometimes referred to as *C85*.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] In 1986, another Draft Standard was released, sometimes referred to as *C86*.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] The prerelease Standard C was published in 1988, and sometimes referred to as *C88*.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] The ANSI standard was completed in 1989 and ratified as ANSI X3.159-1989 "Programming Language C." This version of the language is often referred to as "ANSI C".
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] Later on sometimes the label "C89" is used to distinguish it from C90 but using the same labeling method.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] The same standard as C89 was ratified by ISO/IEC as ISO/IEC 9899:1990, with only formatting changes, which is sometimes referred to as C90.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] Therefore, the terms "C89" and "C90" refer to a language that is virtually identical.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] This standard has been withdrawn by both ANSI/INCITS and ISO/IEC.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] In 1995, the ISO/IEC published an extension, called Amendment 1, for the C standard.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] This was both the first standard with a __STDC_VERSION__ value (199409L) and the first version in which the year in that value did not match the year of publication (1995), leading to common names of both *C94* and *C95*.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] This would happen again in C17 (2018) and C23 (2024), but they are more commonly known by their earlier years, while this standard is often referred to by its later year.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] In March 2000, ANSI adopted the ISO/IEC 9899:1999 standard.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] This standard is commonly referred to as C99.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] This standard has been withdrawn by both ANSI/INCITS and ISO/IEC in favour of C11.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] C11 was officially ratified and published on December 8, 2011.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] Notable features include improved Unicode support, type-generic expressions using the new `_Generic` keyword, a cross-platform multi-threading API (`threads.h`), and atomic types support in both core language and the library (`stdatomic.h`).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] Rather than introducing new language features, it only addresses defects in C11.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] C23 was published in October 2024, and is the current standard for the C programming language.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] C2Y is an informal name for the next revision of the C programming language that is hoped to be released in the later 2020s.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval, including the fifth and final part of TS 18661, a software transactional memory specification, and parallel library extensions.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] ANSI C is supported by almost all the widely used compilers.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] GCC and Clang are two major C compilers popular today, both based on the C11 with updates including changes from later specifications such as C17.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] Any source code written *only* in standard C and without any hardware dependent assumptions is virtually guaranteed to compile correctly on any platform with a conforming C implementation.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] To mitigate the differences between K&R C and the ANSI C standard, the `__STDC__` ("standard c") macro can be used to split code into ANSI and K&R sections.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] In the above example, a prototype is used in a function declaration for ANSI compliant implementations, while an obsolescent non-prototype declaration is used otherwise.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] Those are still ANSI-compliant as of C99.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-c] Note how this code checks both definition and evaluation: this is because some implementations may set `__STDC__` to zero to indicate non-ANSI compliance.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] ANSI sequences were introduced in the 1970s to replace vendor-specific sequences and became widespread in the computer equipment market by the early 1980s.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Although hardware text terminals have become increasingly rare in the 21st century, the relevance of the ANSI standard persists because a great majority of terminal emulators and command consoles interpret at least a portion of the ANSI standard.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Almost all manufacturers of video terminals added vendor-specific escape sequences to perform operations such as placing the cursor at arbitrary positions on the screen.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The Hazeltine 1500 had a similar feature, invoked using `~`, `DC1` and then the X and Y positions separated with a comma.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] While the two terminals had identical functionality in this regard, different control sequences had to be used to invoke them.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] As these sequences were different for different terminals, elaborate libraries such as termcap ("terminal capabilities") and utilities such as tput had to be created so programs could use the same API to work with any terminal.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] In addition, many of these terminals required sending numbers (such as row and column) as the binary values of the characters; for some programming languages, and for systems that did not use ASCII internally, it was often difficult to turn a number into the correct character.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The ANSI standard attempted to address these problems by making a command set that all terminals would use and requiring all numeric information to be transmitted as ASCII numbers.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The first standard in the series was **ECMA-48**, adopted in 1976.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] It was a continuation of a series of character coding standards, the first one being ECMA-6 from 1965, a 7-bit standard from which ISO 646 originates.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The name "ANSI escape sequence" dates from 1979 when ANSI adopted ANSI X3.64.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The ANSI X3L2 committee collaborated with the ECMA committee TC 1 to produce nearly identical standards.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] These two standards were merged into an international standard, ISO 6429.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] In 1994, ANSI withdrew its standard in favor of the international standard.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The first popular video terminal to support these sequences was the Digital VT100, introduced in 1978.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This model was very successful in the market, which sparked a variety of VT100 clones, among the earliest and most popular of which was the much more affordable Zenith Z-19 in 1979.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Others included the Qume QVT-108, Televideo TVI-970, Wyse WY-99GT as well as optional "VT100" or "VT103" or "ANSI" modes with varying degrees of compatibility on many other brands.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The popularity of these gradually led to more and more software (especially bulletin board systems and other online services) assuming the escape sequences worked, leading to almost all new terminals and emulator programs supporting them.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] In 1981, ANSI X3.64 was adopted for use in the US government by FIPS publication 86.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Later, the US government stopped duplicating industry standards, so FIPS pub.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] ECMA-48 has been updated several times and is currently at its 5th edition, from 1991.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] It is also adopted by ISO and IEC as standard **ISO/IEC 6429**.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] A version is adopted as a Japanese Industrial Standard, as JIS X 0211.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Related standards include ITU T.61, the Teletex standard, and the **ISO/IEC 8613**, the Open Document Architecture standard (mainly ISO/IEC 8613-6 or ITU T.416).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The two systems share many escape codes with the ANSI system, with extensions that are not necessarily meaningful to computer terminals.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Both systems quickly fell into disuse, but ECMA-48 does mark the extensions used in them as reserved.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] In the early 1980s, large amounts of software directly used these sequences to update screen displays.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This included everything on VMS (which assumed DEC terminals), most software designed to be portable on CP/M home computers, and significant amounts of Unix software, as it was easier to use than the termcap libraries.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Terminal emulators for communicating with remote machines almost always implement ANSI escape codes.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This includes anything written to communicate with bulletin-board systems on home and personal computers.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] On Unix terminal emulators such as xterm also can communicate with software running on the same machine, and thus software running in X11 under a terminal emulator could assume the ability to write these sequences.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] As computers got more powerful even built-in displays started supporting them, allowing software to be portable between CP/M systems.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] There were attempts to extend the escape sequences to support printers and as an early PDF-like document storage format, the Open Document Architecture.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The IBM PC, introduced in 1981, did not support these or any other escape sequences for updating the screen.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Only a few control characters (BEL, CR, LF, BS) were interpreted by the underlying BIOS.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Any display effects had to be done with BIOS calls, which were notoriously slow, or by directly manipulating the IBM PC hardware.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This made any interesting software non-portable and led to the need to duplicate details of the display hardware in PC Clones.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] DOS version 2.0 included an optional device driver named ANSI.SYS.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Poor performance, and the fact that it was not installed by default, meant software rarely (if ever) took advantage of it.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The Windows Console did not support ANSI escape sequences, nor did Microsoft provide any method to enable them.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Some replacements such as JP Software's TCC (formerly 4NT), Michael J.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Mefford's ANSI.COM, Jason Hood's ANSICON and Maximus5's ConEmu enabled ANSI escape sequences.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Software such as the Python colorama package or Cygwin modified text in-process as it was sent to the console, extracting the ANSI Escape sequences and emulating them with Windows calls.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] In 2016, Microsoft released the Windows 10 version 1511 update which unexpectedly implemented support for ANSI escape sequences, over three decades after the debut of Windows.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This was done alongside Windows Subsystem for Linux, apparently to allow Unix-like terminal-based software to use the Windows Console.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Windows PowerShell 5.1 enabled this by default, and PowerShell 6 made it possible to embed the necessary ESC character into a string with `e.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Windows Terminal, introduced in 2019, supports the sequences by default.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Since Windows 11 22H2 and Windows Terminal 1.15, Windows Terminal replaces Windows Console as the default.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Almost all users assume some functions of some single-byte characters.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The general format for an ANSI-compliant escape sequence is defined by ANSI X3.41 (equivalent to ECMA-35 or ISO/IEC 2022).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The escape sequences consist only of bytes in the range 0x20—0x7F (all the non-control ASCII characters), and can be parsed without looking ahead.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The behavior when a control character, a byte with the high bit set, or a byte that is not part of any valid sequence is encountered before the end is undefined.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x40 to 0x5F, the escape sequence is of type `Fe`.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Its interpretation is delegated to the applicable C1 control code standard.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Accordingly, all escape sequences corresponding to C1 control codes from ANSI X3.64 / ECMA-48 follow this format.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The standard says that, in 8-bit environments, the control functions corresponding to type `Fe` escape sequences (those from the set of C1 control codes) can be represented as single bytes in the 0x80–0x9F range.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This is possible in character encodings conforming to the provisions for an 8-bit code made in ISO 2022, such as the ISO 8859 series.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] However, in character encodings used on modern devices such as UTF-8 or CP-1252, those codes are often used for other purposes, so only the 2-byte sequence is typically used.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] In the case of UTF-8, representing a C1 control code via the C1 Controls and Latin-1 Supplement block results in a different two-byte code (e.g.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] 0xC2,0x8E for U+008E), but no space is saved this way.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] All common sequences just use the parameters as a series of semicolon-separated numbers such as `1;2;3`.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Missing numbers are treated as `0` (`1;;3` acts like the middle number is `0`, and no parameters at all in `ESC[m` acts like a `0` reset code).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Some sequences (such as CUU) treat `0` as `1` in order to make missing parameters useful.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] A subset of arrangements was declared "private" so that terminal manufacturers could insert their own sequences without conflicting with the standard.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Sequences containing the parameter bytes `<=>?` or the final bytes 0x70–0x7E (`p–z{|}~`) are private.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The behavior of the terminal is undefined in the case where a CSI sequence contains any character outside of the range 0x20–0x7E.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] These illegal characters are either C0 control characters (the range 0–0x1F), DEL (0x7F), or bytes with the high bit set.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Possible responses are to ignore the byte, to process it immediately, and furthermore whether to continue with the CSI sequence, to abort it immediately, or to ignore the rest of it.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The control sequence `CSI *n* m`, named Select Graphic Rendition (SGR), sets display attributes.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Several attributes can be set in the same sequence, separated by semicolons.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Each display attribute remains in effect until a following occurrence of SGR resets it.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] If no codes are given, `CSI m` is treated as `CSI 0 m` (reset / normal).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The original specification only had 8 colors, and just gave them names.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The SGR parameters 30–37 selected the foreground color, while 40–47 selected the background.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Quite a few terminals implemented "bold" (SGR code 1) as a brighter color rather than a different font, thus providing 8 additional foreground colors.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Usually you could not get these as background colors, though sometimes inverse video (SGR code 7) would allow that.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Examples: to get black letters on white background use `ESC[30;47m`, to get red use `ESC[31m`, to get bright red use `ESC[1;31m`.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] To reset colors to their defaults, use `ESC[39;49m` (not supported on some terminals), or reset all attributes with `ESC[0m`.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Later terminals added the ability to directly specify the "bright" colors with 90–97 and 100–107.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The chart below shows a few examples of how classical standards and modern terminal emulators translate the 4-bit color codes into 24-bit color codes.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The colors displayed by these values vary across terminal/emulator implementations as the recognized ECMA-48 and ITU's T.416 specifications do not define a specific color palette for this lookup table.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] While it is common to use the above formula for the color palette, in particular the algorithm and choice of colors for the 16-231 cube values differs between implementations.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The color palette and algorithm used by XTerm is specified below as a sample.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] There has also been a similar but incompatible 88-color encoding using the same escape sequence, seen in `rxvt` and `xterm-88color`.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] As "true color" graphic cards with 16 to 24 bits of color became common, applications began to support 24-bit colors.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Terminal emulators supporting setting 24-bit foreground and background colors with escape sequences include Xterm, KDE's Konsole, and iTerm, as well as all libvte based terminals, including GNOME Terminal.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This syntax, initially implemented in XTerm, is based on a reading of the ISO/IEC 8613-6 specification, specifically that SGR 38 / SGR 48 followed by the parameter "2" can specify a "direct color" in RGB space..
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] As the first widely-used implementation, this specification of RGB values using semicolon separators is widely supported by terminal emulators that include 24-bit color support.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] As with the 8-bit color codes, there is a very similar specification of 24-bit color in the ITU's T.416 Open Document Architecture (ODA) and interchange format: Character content architectures, which was adopted as ISO/IEC 8613-6 but ended up as a commercial failure.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] where `Color-Space` indicates the Color-Space associated with the given tolerance: `0` for CIELUV or `1` for CIELAB.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The semicolon-based RGB specification is the most widely supported, but both it and the RGB variant of ITU T.416 are supported by many terminal emulators.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This system, although poorly documented, became widespread enough for Fedora and RHEL to consider using it as a simpler and more universal detection mechanism compared to querying the now-updated libraries.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Some terminal emulators (urxvt, Konsole) set `$COLORFGBG` to report the color scheme of the terminal (mainly light vs. dark background).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This behavior originated in S-Lang and is used by vim.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Gnome-terminal refuses to add this behavior, as the syntax for the value is not agreed upon, the value cannot be changed upon a runtime change of the palette, and more "proper" xterm OSC 4/10/11 sequences already exist.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] It has become conventional to use the `NO_COLOR` environment variable to disable colors unconditionally.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Most Operating System Command sequences were defined by Xterm, but many are also supported by other terminal emulators.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] For historical reasons, Xterm can end the command with `BEL` (0x07) as well as the standard `ST` (0x9C or 0x1B 0x5C).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] For example, Xterm allows the icon name and window title to be set by `ESC ]0;this is the title BEL`.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] A non-xterm extension is the hyperlink, `ESC ]8;;link ST` from 2017, used by VTE, iTerm2, and mintty, among others.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The Linux console uses `ESC ] P n rr gg bb` to change the palette, which, if hard-coded into an application, may hang other terminals.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] However, appending `ST` will be ignored by Linux and form a proper, ignorable sequence for other terminals.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x60—0x7E, the escape sequence is of type `Fs`.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This type is used for control functions individually registered with the ISO-IR registry.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] A table of these is listed under ISO/IEC 2022.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x30—0x3F, the escape sequence is of type `Fp`, which is set apart for up to sixteen private-use control functions.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x20—0x2F, the escape sequence is of type `nF`.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Said byte is followed by any number of additional bytes in this range, and then a byte in the range 0x30-0x7E.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] These escape sequences are further subcategorised by the low two bits of the first byte, e.g.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] "type `2F`" for sequences where the first byte is 0x22; and by whether the final byte is in the range 0x30—0x3F indicating private use (e.g.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Most of the `nFt` sequences are for changing the current character set, and are listed in ISO/IEC 2022.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] If the first byte is '#' the public sequences are reserved for additional ISO-IR registered individual control functions.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] No such sequences are presently registered.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Type `3Fp` sequences (which includes ones starting with '#') are available for private-use control functions.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] `CSI 2 J` — This clears the screen and, on some devices, locates the cursor to the y,x position 1,1 (upper left corner).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The green may be a dark, dull green, so you may wish to enable Bold with the sequence `CSI 1 m` which would make it bright green, or combined as `CSI 32 ; 1 m`.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Some implementations use the Bold state to make the character Bright.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] `CSI 0 ; 6 8 ; "DIR" ; 13 p` — This reassigns the key F10 to send to the keyboard buffer the string "DIR" and ENTER, which in the DOS command line would display the contents of the current directory.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] (MS-DOS ANSI.SYS only) This was sometimes used for ANSI bombs.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This is a private-use code (as indicated by the letter p), using a non-standard extension to include a string-valued parameter.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Following the letter of the standard would consider the sequence to end at the letter D.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] `CSI s` — This saves the cursor position.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Using the sequence `CSI u` will restore it to the position.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Say the current cursor position is 7(y) and 10(x).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The sequence `CSI s` will save those two numbers.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Now you can move to a different cursor position, such as 20(y) and 3(x), using the sequence `CSI 20 ; 3 H` or `CSI 20 ; 3 f`.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Now if you use the sequence CSI u the cursor position will return to 7(y) and 10(x).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Some terminals require the DEC sequences `ESC 7` / `ESC 8` instead which is more widely supported.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] ANSI escape codes are often used in UNIX and UNIX-like terminals to provide syntax highlighting.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] For example, on compatible terminals, the following *list* command color-codes file and directory names by type.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Users can employ escape codes in their scripts by including them as part of *standard output* or *standard error*.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] For example, the following GNU *sed* command embellishes the output of the *make* command by displaying lines containing words starting with "WARN" in reverse video and words starting with "ERR" in bright yellow on a dark red background (letter case is ignored).
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The representations of the codes are highlighted.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The following Bash function flashes the terminal (by alternately sending reverse and normal video mode codes) until the user presses a key.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] It can be used to alert a programmer when a lengthy command terminates, such as with `make ; flasher` .
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The following command will reset the console, similar to the command `reset` on modern Linux systems; however it should work even on older Linux systems and on other (non-Linux) UNIX variants.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] This following program creates a table of numbers from 0 to 109, each of which is displayed in the format specified by the Select Graphic Rendition escape sequence using that number as the graphic rendition code.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Pressing special keys on the keyboard, as well as outputting many xterm CSI, DCS, or OSC sequences, often produces a CSI, DCS, or OSC sequence, sent from the terminal to the computer as though the user typed it.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] When typing input on a terminal keypresses outside the normal main alphanumeric keyboard area can be sent to the host as ANSI sequences.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] For keys that have an equivalent output function, such as the cursor keys, these often mirror the output sequences.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] However, for most keypresses there isn't an equivalent output sequence to use.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] There are several encoding schemes, and unfortunately most terminals mix sequences from different schemes, so host software has to be able to deal with input sequences using any scheme.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] To complicate the matter, the VT terminals themselves have two schemes of input, *normal mode* and *application mode* that can be switched by the application.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] If the terminating character is '~', the first number must be present and is a keycode number, the second number is an optional modifier value.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] If the terminating character is a letter, the letter is the keycode value, and the optional number is the modifier value.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The modifier value defaults to 1, and after subtracting 1 is a bitmap of modifier keys being pressed: Meta+Ctrl+Alt+⇧ Shift.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] `<esc>[A` to `<esc>[D` are the same as the ANSI output sequences.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] The `<modifier>` is normally omitted if no modifier keys are pressed, but most implementations always emit the `<modifier>` for F1–F4.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Xterm has a comprehensive documentation page on the various function-key and mouse input sequence schemes from DEC's VT terminals and various other terminals it emulates.
[src:iec-62700/ansi-escape-code] Thomas Dickey has added a lot of support to it over time; he also maintains a list of default keys used by other terminal emulators for comparison.
[src:iec-62700/atx] ATX is a commonly used motherboard and power supply hardware form factor for desktop computers.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The ATX form factor defined a general mounting point placement and I/O panel size that smaller motherboards share (such as microATX, FlexATX, and Mini-ITX), making them backwards compatible in many computer cases.
[src:iec-62700/atx] As of 2012, ATX is the most common motherboard design.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Other standards for smaller boards (including microATX, FlexATX, nano-ITX, and mini-ITX) keep the basic rear layout but reduce the size of the board and the number of expansion slots.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Dimensions of a full-size ATX board are 12 × 9.6 in (305 × 244 mm) which means microATX boards fit in many ATX chassis.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The ATX specifications were patented by David Dent at Intel and co-developed with Astec America, a major manufacturer of power supplies at the time.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The inaugural version 1.0 of the ATX specification was unveiled by Intel in July 1995.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Since then, ATX has been revised numerous times.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The most recent ATX motherboard specification is version 2.2.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The most recent ATX12V power supply unit specification is ATX 3.0 released in February 2022.
[src:iec-62700/atx] EATX, or E-ATX (Extended ATX), is a term that refers to motherboards larger than the ATX standard.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Motherboards labeled E-ATX commonly share dimensions with the SSI-EEB (Server System Infrastructure - Enterprise Electronics Bay) standard (12 x 13 in), however, it is not a guarantee.
[src:iec-62700/atx] While some dual-CPU-socket motherboards have been implemented in ATX, the extra size of EATX makes it the typical form factor for dual-socket systems and for single-socket systems with a large number of memory slots (or more than two memory channels).
[src:iec-62700/atx] In 2004, Intel announced the BTX (Balanced Technology eXtended) standard, intended as a replacement for ATX.
[src:iec-62700/atx] While some manufacturers adopted the new standard, Intel discontinued any future development of BTX in 2006.
[src:iec-62700/atx] As of 2026, the ATX design still remains the standard for personal computers.
[src:iec-62700/atx] On the back of the computer case, some major changes were made to the AT standard.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Originally AT style cases had only a keyboard connector and expansion slots for add-on card backplates.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Any other onboard interfaces (such as serial and parallel ports) had to be connected via flying leads to connectors which were mounted either on spaces provided by the case or brackets placed in unused expansion slot positions.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The ATX standard specified a rectangular area on the back of the system where motherboard manufacturers can arrange ports any way they want.
[src:iec-62700/atx] A number of general patterns (depending on which ports the motherboard offers) have been used by most manufacturers.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Cases are usually fitted with a snap-out panel, also known as an I/O plate or I/O shield, in one of the common arrangements.
[src:iec-62700/atx] I/O plates are usually included with retail motherboards for installation in any suitable case.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The computer will operate correctly without a plate fitted, but there will be open gaps in the case which may compromise the EMI/RFI screening and allow the ingress of dirt and random foreign bodies.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Panels were made that fit an AT motherboard in an ATX case.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Some ATX motherboards come with an integrated I/O plate.
[src:iec-62700/atx] ATX also made the PS/2-style mini-DIN keyboard and mouse connectors ubiquitous.
[src:iec-62700/atx] AT systems used a 5-pin DIN connector for the keyboard and were generally used with serial port mice (although PS/2 mouse ports were also found on some systems).
[src:iec-62700/atx] Many modern motherboards are phasing out the PS/2-style keyboard and mouse connectors in favor of the more modern Universal Serial Bus.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Other legacy connectors that are slowly being phased out of modern ATX motherboards include 25-pin parallel ports and 9-pin RS-232 serial ports.
[src:iec-62700/atx] In their place are onboard peripheral ports such as Ethernet, FireWire, eSATA, audio ports (both analog and S/PDIF), video (analog D-sub, DVI, HDMI, or DisplayPort), extra USB ports, and Wi-Fi.
[src:iec-62700/atx] A notable issue with the ATX specification was that it was last revised when power supplies were normally placed at the top of many old computer cases rather than at the bottom, as with many modern computer cases.
[src:iec-62700/atx] This has led to some problematic standard locations for ports, in particular the 4/8 pin CPU power, which is normally located along the top edge of the board, convenient for top-mounted power supplies.
[src:iec-62700/atx] This makes it very difficult for cables from bottom-mounted power supplies to reach, and commonly requires a special cutout in the back plane for the cable to come in from behind and bend around the board, making insertion and wire management very difficult.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Many power supply cables barely or fail to reach, or are too stiff to make the bend, and extensions are sometimes required due to this placement.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Modern power supplies often have longer cables to alleviate this issue.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Several ATX-derived designs have been specified that use the same power supply, mountings and basic back panel arrangement, but set different standards for the size of the board and number of expansion slots.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Standard ATX provides seven slots at 0.8 in (20 mm) spacing; the popular microATX size removes 2.4 inches (61 mm) and three slots, leaving four.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Here width refers to the distance along the external connector edge, while depth is from front to rear.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Note each larger size inherits all previous (smaller) colors area.
[src:iec-62700/atx] AOpen has conflated the term Mini ATX with a more recent 15 × 15 cm (5.9 × 5.9 in) design.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Since references to Mini ATX have been removed from ATX specifications since the adoption of microATX, the AOpen definition is the more contemporary term and the one listed above is apparently only of historical significance.
[src:iec-62700/atx] This sounds contradictory to the now common Mini-ITX standard (17 × 17 cm (6.7 × 6.7 in)), which is a potential source of confusion.
[src:iec-62700/atx] A number of manufacturers have added one to three additional expansion slots (at the standard 0.8 inch spacing) to the standard 12-inch ATX motherboard width.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Form factors considered obsolete in 1999 included Baby-AT, full size AT, and the semi-proprietary LPX for low-profile cases.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Proprietary motherboard designs such as those by Compaq, Packard-Bell, Hewlett Packard and others existed, and were not interchangeable with multi-manufacturer boards and cases.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Portable and notebook computers and some 19-inch rackmount servers have custom motherboards unique to their particular products.
[src:iec-62700/atx] While E-ATX and SSI EEB (Server System Infrastructure (SSI) Forum's Enterprise Electronics Bay (EEB)) share the same dimensions, the screw holes of the two standards do not all align; rendering them incompatible.
[src:iec-62700/atx] In 2008, Foxconn unveiled a Foxconn F1 motherboard prototype, which has the same width as a standard ATX motherboard, but an extended 14.4" length to accommodate 10 slots.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The firm called the new 14.4 × 9.6 in (366 × 244 mm) design of this motherboard "Ultra ATX" in its CES 2008 showing.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Also unveiled during the January 2008 CES was the Lian Li Armorsuit PC-P80 case with 10 slots designed for the motherboard.
[src:iec-62700/atx] In 2010, EVGA Corporation released a new motherboard, the "Super Record 2", or SR-2, whose size surpasses that of the "EVGA X58 Classified 4-Way SLI".
[src:iec-62700/atx] The new board is designed to accommodate two Dual QPI LGA1366 socket CPUs (e.g.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Intel Xeon), similar to that of the Intel Skulltrail motherboard that could accommodate two Intel Core 2 Quad processors and has a total of seven PCI-E slots and 12 DDR3 RAM slots.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The ATX specification requires the power supply to produce three main outputs, +3.3 V, +5 V and +12 V.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Low-power −12 V and +5 VSB (standby) supplies are also required.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The −12 V supply is primarily used to provide the negative supply voltage for RS-232 ports and is also used by one pin on conventional PCI slots primarily to provide a reference voltage for some models of sound cards.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The 5 VSB supply is used to produce trickle power to provide the soft-power feature of ATX when a PC is turned off, as well as powering the real-time clock to conserve the charge of the CMOS battery.
[src:iec-62700/atx] A −5 V output was originally required because it was supplied on the ISA bus.
[src:iec-62700/atx] However, it was removed in later versions of the ATX standard once ISA expansion slots became obsolete.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Originally, the motherboard was powered by one 20-pin connector.
[src:iec-62700/atx] An ATX power supply provides a number of peripheral power connectors and (in modern systems) two connectors for the motherboard: an 8-pin (or 4+4-pin) auxiliary connector providing additional power to the CPU and a main 24-pin power supply connector, an extension of the original 20-pin version.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The connector pin pitch is 4.20 mm (about one sixth of an inch).
[src:iec-62700/atx] Generally, supply voltages must be within ±5% of their nominal values at all times.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The little-used negative supply voltages, however, have a ±10% tolerance.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The 20–24-pin Molex Mini-Fit Jr. has a power rating of, 9 amperes maximum per pin).
[src:iec-62700/atx] As large server motherboards and 3D graphics cards have required progressively more and more power to operate, it has been necessary to revise and extend the standard beyond the original 20-pin connector, to allow more current using multiple additional pins in parallel.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The low circuit voltage is the restriction on power flow through each connector pin; at the maximum rated voltage, a single Mini-Fit Jr pin would be capable of 4800 watts.
[src:iec-62700/atx] That last dimension, the 140 mm depth, is frequently varied, with depths of 160, 180, 200 and 230 mm used to accommodate higher power, larger fan and/or modular connectors.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Original AT cases (flat case style) have an integrated power switch that protruded from the power supply and sits flush with a hole in the AT chassis.
[src:iec-62700/atx] It utilizes a paddle-style DPST switch and is similar to the PC and PC-XT style power supplies.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Later AT (so-called "Baby AT") and LPX style computer cases have a power button that is directly connected to the system computer power supply (PSU).
[src:iec-62700/atx] The general configuration is a double-pole latching mains voltage switch with the four pins connected to wires from a four-core cable.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The wires are either soldered to the power button (making it difficult to replace the power supply if it failed) or blade receptacles were used.
[src:iec-62700/atx] An ATX power supply is typically controlled by an electronic switch connected to the power button on the computer case and allows the computer to be turned off by the operating system.
[src:iec-62700/atx] In addition, many ATX power supplies have a manual switch on the back that also ensures no power is being sent to the components.
[src:iec-62700/atx] When the switch on the power supply is turned off, the computer cannot be turned on with the front power button.
[src:iec-62700/atx] ATX uses one large, keyed connector which can not be connected incorrectly.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The new connector also provides a 3.3 volt source, removing the need for motherboards to derive this voltage from the 5 V rail.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Some motherboards, particularly those manufactured after the introduction of ATX but whilst LPX equipment was still in use, support both LPX and ATX PSUs.
[src:iec-62700/atx] A minimum load on one or more voltages may be required (varies by model and vendor); the standard does not specify operation without a minimum load and a conforming PSU may shut down, output incorrect voltages, or otherwise malfunction, but will not be hazardous or damaged.
[src:iec-62700/atx] An ATX power supply is not a replacement for a current-limited bench laboratory DC power supply; instead it is better described as a bulk DC power supply.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The original ATX specification called for a power supply to be located near to the CPU with the power supply fan drawing in cooling air from outside the chassis and directing it onto the processor.
[src:iec-62700/atx] It was thought that in this configuration, cooling of the processor would be achievable without the need of an active heatsink.
[src:iec-62700/atx] This recommendation was removed from later specifications; modern ATX power supplies usually exhaust air from the case.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The power distribution specification defined that most of the PSU's power should be provided on 5 V and 3.3 V rails, because most of the electronic components (CPU, RAM, chipset, PCI, AGP and ISA cards) used 5 V or 3.3 V for power supply.
[src:iec-62700/atx] While designing the Pentium 4 platform in 1999/2000, the standard 20-pin ATX power connector was found insufficient to meet increasing power-line requirements; the standard was significantly revised into ATX12V 1.0 (ATX12V 1.x is sometimes inaccurately called ATX-P4).
[src:iec-62700/atx] ATX12V 1.x was also adopted by AMD Athlon XP and Athlon 64 systems.
[src:iec-62700/atx] However, some early model Athlon XP and MP boards (including some server boards) and later model lower-end motherboards do not have the 4-pin connector as described below.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Numbering of the ATX revisions may be a little confusing: ATX refers to the design, and goes up to version 2.2 in 2004 (with the 24 pins of ATX12V 2.0), while ATX12V describes only the PSU.
[src:iec-62700/atx] For instance, ATX 2.03 is quite commonly seen on PSUs from 2000 and 2001 and often includes the P4 12V connector, even if the norm itself did not define it yet.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Formally called the *+12 V Power Connector*, this is commonly referred to as the **P4 connector** because this was first needed to support the Pentium 4 processor.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Before the Pentium 4, processors were generally powered from the 5 V rail.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Later processors operate at much lower voltages, typically around 1 V and some draw over 100 A.
[src:iec-62700/atx] It is infeasible to provide power at such low voltages and high currents from a standard system power supply, so the Pentium 4 established the practice of generating it with a DC-to-DC converter on the motherboard next to the processor, powered by the 4-pin 12 V connector.
[src:iec-62700/atx] This is a minor revision from August 2000.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The power on the 3.3 V rail was slightly increased and other smaller changes were made.
[src:iec-62700/atx] A relatively minor revision from January 2002.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The only significant change was that the −5 V rail was no longer required (it became optional).
[src:iec-62700/atx] This voltage was required by the ISA bus, which is no longer present on almost all modern computers.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Introduced in April 2003 (a month after 2.0).
[src:iec-62700/atx] This standard introduced some changes, mostly minor.
[src:iec-62700/atx] ATX12V 2.x brought a significant design change regarding power distribution.
[src:iec-62700/atx] By analyzing the power demands of then-current PCs, it was determined that it would be much cheaper and more practical to power most PC components from 12 V rails, instead of from 3.3 V and 5 V rails.
[src:iec-62700/atx] In particular, PCI Express expansion cards take much of their power from the 12 V rail (up to 5.5 A), while the older AGP graphics cards took only up to 1 A on 12 V and up to 6 A on 3.3 V.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The CPU is also driven by a 12 V rail, while it was done by a 5 V rail on older PCs (before the Pentium 4).
[src:iec-62700/atx] This is a minor revision from June 2004.
[src:iec-62700/atx] An errant reference for the −5 V rail was removed.
[src:iec-62700/atx] This is a minor revision from March 2005.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The power was slightly increased on all rails.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Efficiency requirements changed: minimum 65% at light load, 72% at typical load, and 70% at full load.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Introduced recommended minimum values of 75% at light load, 80% at typical load, and 77% at full load.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Also released in March 2005 it includes corrections and specifies High Current Series wire terminals for 24-pin ATX motherboard and 4-pin +12 V power connectors.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Recommended efficiency was increased to 80% (with at least 70% required) and the 12 V minimum load requirement was lowered.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Higher efficiency generally results in less power consumption (and less waste heat) and the 80% recommendation brings supplies in line with new Energy Star 4.0 mandates.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The reduced load requirement allows compatibility with processors that draw very little power during startup.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The absolute over-current limit of 240 VA per rail was removed, allowing 12 V lines to provide more than 20 A per rail.
[src:iec-62700/atx] This revision became effective in February 2008.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The ATX12V 2.4 specifications were published in August 2012.
[src:iec-62700/atx] It is specified in Revision 1.31 of the *Power Supply Design Guide for Desktop Platform Form Factors*, which names this as ATX12V version 2.4.
[src:iec-62700/atx] In July 2012, revision 1.3 of the *Power Supply Design Guide for Desktop Platform Form Factors* made inclusion of the floppy drive connector optional, instead of mandatory.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The specifications for ATXV12 2.51 were released in September 2021 and introduced support for *Alternative Low Power Mode (ALPM)* which supersedes the traditional S3 power state.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Windows 10 implements this functionality as *Modern Standby*.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Power supply fans are also recommended to turn on with at least a two second delay for an improved user experience.
[src:iec-62700/atx] This version also stated that the floppy drive connector should be excluded from PSUs, as opposed to merely being optional, and marked that connector's section in the specification as "For Historical Reference Only".
[src:iec-62700/atx] The specifications for ATX12V 2.53 were released in December 2021 and constitute another minor update to the ATX standard.
[src:iec-62700/atx] ATX12V 2.53 makes further recommendations on efficiency and references the Energy Star *Computers Specification Version 8.0* which was finalized in April 2020.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The specifications for ATX 3.0 were released in February 2022.
[src:iec-62700/atx] It includes the new 16-pin 12VHPWR connector that can deliver up to 600 W for H+ and up to 675 W in H++ to graphics cards.
[src:iec-62700/atx] These incorporate data lines for components to negotiate power capabilities with the PSU so they do not draw more power than the PSU is capable of delivering.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The specification also has more strict requirements for handling spikes, two times the nominal output for 100 microseconds.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The −12 V supply is now specified as optional on the ATX motherboard connector, and some PSU manufacturers (e.g.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Corsair) have begun removing the −12 V supply from their PSUs.
[src:iec-62700/atx] However, as of 2025, some motherboards (e.g. recent designs from ASRock) still use the −12 V supply - typically to power the amplifier for on-board audio - and functions that use it will not work as expected when paired with a PSU that does not provide a −12 V supply.
[src:iec-62700/atx] ATX 3.1 replaces the 12VHPWR power connector with the 12V-2x6 power connector and reduces required power loss hold-up time from 17 milliseconds to 12 milliseconds.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Standing for **ATX 12-volt-only**, this is a new specification published by Intel in 2019, aimed at pre-built systems in the first run, and stricter power efficiency requirements by the California Energy Commission going into effect in 2021.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Several OEMs were already using a similar design with proprietary connectors and this effectively standardizes those.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Under this standard, power supplies provide only a 12 V output.
[src:iec-62700/atx] ATX12VO introduces a new 10-pin connector to supply the motherboard, replacing the 24-pin ATX12V connector.
[src:iec-62700/atx] This greatly simplifies power supplies, but moves DC-to-DC conversion and some connectors to the motherboard instead.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Notably, SATA power connectors, which include 3.3 V and 5 V pins, need to move to the motherboard instead of being connected directly to the power supply.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Connector pinout per Intel ATX12VO (12V Only) Desktop Power Supply Design Guide.
[src:iec-62700/atx] SFX (Small Form-Factor eXtended) is merely a design for a small form factor (SFF) power supply casing (such as those using microATX, FlexATX, nano-ITX, mini-ITX, and NLX), with the power specifications almost identical to ATX.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Thus, an SFX power supply is mostly pin-compatible with the ATX power supply as the main difference is its reduced dimensions; the only electrical difference is that the SFX specifications do not require the −5 V rail.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Since −5 V is required only by some ISA-bus expansion cards, this is not an issue with modern hardware and decreases productions costs.
[src:iec-62700/atx] As a result, ATX pin 20, which carried −5 V, is absent in current power supplies; it was optional in ATX and ATX12V version 1.2 and deleted as of ATX version 1.3.
[src:iec-62700/atx] SFX has dimensions of 125 × 63.5 × 100 mm (width × height × depth), with a 60 mm fan, compared with the standard ATX dimensions of 150 × 86 × 140 mm.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Optional 80 or 40 mm fan replacement increases or decreases the height of an SFX unit.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Some manufacturers and retailers incorrectly market SFX power supplies as μATX or MicroATX power supplies.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Some manufacturers make SFX-L dimensions of 125 × 63.5 × 130 mm to accommodate a 120 mm fan.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Thin Form Factor is another small power supply design with standard ATX specification connectors.
[src:iec-62700/atx] WTX power supplies provide a WTX style motherboard connector which is incompatible with the standard ATX motherboard connector.
[src:iec-62700/atx] This is an ATX12V power supply derivative made by AMD to power its Athlon MP (dual processor) platform.
[src:iec-62700/atx] It was used only on high-end Athlon MP motherboards.
[src:iec-62700/atx] It has a special 8-pin supplemental connector for motherboard, so an AMD GES PSU is required for such motherboards (those motherboards will not work with ATX(12 V) PSUs).
[src:iec-62700/atx] ATX12V-GES 24-pin P1 motherboard connector.
[src:iec-62700/atx] ATX12V-GES 8-pin P2 motherboard connector.
[src:iec-62700/atx] EPS12V is defined in Server System Infrastructure (SSI) and used primarily by SMP/multi-core systems such as Core 2, Core i7, Opteron and Xeon.
[src:iec-62700/atx] It has a 24-pin ATX motherboard connector (same as ATX12V v2.x), an 8-pin secondary connector and an optional 4-pin tertiary connector.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Rather than include the extra cable, many power supply makers implement the 8-pin connector as two combinable 4-pin connectors to ensure backwards compatibility with ATX12V motherboards.
[src:iec-62700/atx] High-performance video card power demands dramatically increased during the 2000s and some high-end graphics cards have power demands that exceed AGP or PCIe slot capabilities.
[src:iec-62700/atx] For these cards, supplementary power was delivered through a standard 4-pin peripheral or floppy power connector.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Midrange and high-end PCIe graphics cards manufactured after 2004 typically use a standard 6- or 8-pin PCIe power connector directly from the PSU.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Efficiency in power supplies means the extent to which power is not wasted in converting electricity from a household supply to regulated DC.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Computer power supplies vary from around 70% to over 90% efficiency.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Various initiatives exist to improve the efficiency of computer power supplies.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Climate Savers Computing Initiative promotes energy saving and reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by encouraging development and use of more efficient power supplies.
[src:iec-62700/atx] 80 PLUS certifies a variety of efficiency levels for power supplies and encourages their use via financial incentives.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Efficient power supplies also save money by wasting less power; as a result they use less electricity to power the same computer, and they emit less waste heat which results in significant energy savings on central air conditioning in the summer.
[src:iec-62700/atx] The gains of using an efficient power supply are more substantial in computers that use a lot of power.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Although a power supply with a larger than needed power rating will have an extra margin of safety against overloading, such a unit is often less efficient and wastes more electricity at lower loads than a more appropriately sized unit.
[src:iec-62700/atx] Thus, for a 100 W load, losses for this supply would be 27 W; if the same power supply was put under a 450 W load, for which the supply's efficiency peaks at 89%, the loss would be only 56 W despite supplying 4.5 times the useful power.
[src:iec-62700/atx] For a comparison, a 500-watt power supply carrying the 80 Plus Bronze efficiency rating (which means that such a power supply is designed to be at least 82-percent efficient for loads above 100 W) may provide an 84 percent efficiency for a 100 W load, wasting only 19 W.
[src:iec-62700/iec-62700] The specification was published on 6 February 2014.
[src:iec-62700/iec-62700] Despite being an industry open organization with open participation, the standard has been criticized by some for not being openly available for review.
